{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/diarrhoea-prevention-advice-for-travellers/background-information/causes/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"3a92beb8-79d6-5dae-ab0f-e43917551a50","slug":"causes","fullItemName":"Causes","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 2b263686-2d32-4cf7-93ee-4a64cb77d12a --><h2>What causes it?</h2><!-- end field 2b263686-2d32-4cf7-93ee-4a64cb77d12a -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 9fcf375c-76cb-44bb-bc03-bad3d194eaf9 --><!-- begin field 3285e92a-65b6-42a4-89a5-d07676dbfcfb --><ul><li>Travellers' diarrhoea is caused by an infection with one or more bacteria, viruses, or parasites and depends on the geographical location, with most travellers' diarrhoea occurring during trips to low and middle income countries [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/diarrhoea-prevention-advice-for-travellers/references/\">CATMAT, 2015</a>]. The cause of travelers' diarrhoea is often not found [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/diarrhoea-prevention-advice-for-travellers/references/\">Barrett and Brown, 2018</a>], but using research techniques, infectious agents can be found in 60–80% of people with travellers' diarrhoea<strong> </strong>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/diarrhoea-prevention-advice-for-travellers/references/\">Jiang and DuPont, 2017</a>]. </li><li>Bacteria are the most common cause and are thought to account for 80–90% of cases of travellers' diarrhoea [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/diarrhoea-prevention-advice-for-travellers/references/\">CDC, 2017a</a>]. The clinical picture may vary depending on the infecting pathogen [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/diarrhoea-prevention-advice-for-travellers/references/\">Laaveri et al, 2018</a>]. <ul><li><em>Escherichia coli </em>is the most common pathogen (associated with acute watery diarrhoea), followed by <em>Campylobacter </em>(more severe symptoms including fever and abdominal pain), <em>Shigella</em>, and Salmonella [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/diarrhoea-prevention-advice-for-travellers/references/\">CATMAT, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/diarrhoea-prevention-advice-for-travellers/references/\">CDC, 2017a</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/diarrhoea-prevention-advice-for-travellers/references/\">Laaveri et al, 2018</a>]. Other potential bacterial causes include <em>Vibrio cholerae</em>, <em>Aeromonas</em> spp, <em>Plesiomonas</em> spp, and the newly recognised <em>Acrobacter</em>, <em>Larobacter</em>, and enterotoxigenic <em>Bacteroides fragilis </em>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/diarrhoea-prevention-advice-for-travellers/references/\">Barrett, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/diarrhoea-prevention-advice-for-travellers/references/\">CDC, 2017a</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/diarrhoea-prevention-advice-for-travellers/references/\">Shane, 2017</a>].  <ul><li>Enterotoxigenic <em>E. coli </em>(ETEC) is responsible for about one third of cases of travellers' diarrhoea in people visiting Latin America, the Caribbean, Africa, and South Asia [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/diarrhoea-prevention-advice-for-travellers/references/\">CATMAT, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/diarrhoea-prevention-advice-for-travellers/references/\">Leder, 2015</a>]. Enteroaggregative <em>E. coli </em>(EAEC) and enteropathogenic<em> E. coli </em>(EPEC) are also significant causes of travellers' diarrhoea [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/diarrhoea-prevention-advice-for-travellers/references/\">Jiang and DuPont, 2017</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/diarrhoea-prevention-advice-for-travellers/references/\">Laaveri et al, 2018</a>].  </li><li><em>Campylobacter </em>infection is more prevalent in people visiting South East Asia, and a high number of these cases are resistant to fluoroquinolones [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/diarrhoea-prevention-advice-for-travellers/references/\">Giddings et al, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/diarrhoea-prevention-advice-for-travellers/references/\">Jiang and DuPont, 2017</a>]. It is less common in East and West Africa, South America and the Caribbean [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/diarrhoea-prevention-advice-for-travellers/references/\">Laaveri et al, 2018</a>].  </li></ul></li></ul></li><li>Travellers' diarrhoea can also be caused by viruses (5–8% of cases) [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/diarrhoea-prevention-advice-for-travellers/references/\">CDC, 2017a</a>].  <ul><li>Norovirus and rotavirus are most commonly implicated, with norovirus often associated with outbreaks of diarrhoea on cruise ships [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/diarrhoea-prevention-advice-for-travellers/references/\">CATMAT, 2015</a>].  </li></ul></li><li>Parasites account for less than 2%–12% of cases of  travellers' diarrhoea, depending on the area of travel (less common in Latin America, the Caribbean, and Africa; more common in Asia) [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/diarrhoea-prevention-advice-for-travellers/references/\">CATMAT, 2015</a>].  <ul><li>Giardia intestinalis is the most common protozoal cause of travellers' diarrhoea<em>, </em>with both<em> Entamoeba histolytica, </em>and <em>Cryptosporidium </em>being relatively uncommon. Other causes include <em>Cyclospora</em> (for which the most well documented risk is<em> </em>in Nepal, Peru, Haiti, and Guatemala) and <em>Dientamoeba fragilis</em> [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/diarrhoea-prevention-advice-for-travellers/references/\">CDC, 2017a</a>]. Parasitic pathogens tend to cause more prolonged symptoms, therefore travellers' diarrhoea due to parasites such as <em>Giardia</em> more often needs post-travel medical care [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/diarrhoea-prevention-advice-for-travellers/references/\">CATMAT, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/diarrhoea-prevention-advice-for-travellers/references/\">Leder, 2015</a>]. </li><li>Helminth infection is an uncommon cause of travellers' diarrhoea, although it may be caused by acute heavy hookworm infection or schistosomiasis [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/diarrhoea-prevention-advice-for-travellers/references/\">McGregor and Wright, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/diarrhoea-prevention-advice-for-travellers/references/\">Giddings et al, 2016</a>]. </li></ul></li></ul><p> </p><!-- end field 3285e92a-65b6-42a4-89a5-d07676dbfcfb --><!-- end item 9fcf375c-76cb-44bb-bc03-bad3d194eaf9 -->","topic":{"id":"d5cf1db6-a6d9-54fb-b393-095d8af57067","topicId":"9042b194-f66e-44c6-a91c-76ffa626e3e8","topicName":"Diarrhoea - prevention and advice for travellers","slug":"diarrhoea-prevention-advice-for-travellers","lastRevised":"Last revised in February 2019","chapters":[{"id":"3f7bee04-88e6-5a40-86d5-e39dc29e4059","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"47ddb819-f046-5e92-999c-a3d47a00ede8","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"bdd3d81e-da2b-5807-b257-8dd4d73a596c","fullItemName":"How up-to-d